(the cfg field), returns 0 if the CFG is null, then reads and returns the
exit_block pointer from MIRCFG offset 8 (the exit_block field). These offsets
match the MIRFunction and MIRCFG type definitions in mir.runa.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - two pointer loads. No allocation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. Returns 0 on null function or null CFG so the caller skips return
lowering safely.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_exit_block" that takes mir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_function, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let exit_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 8
    Return exit_block
End Process

@Reasoning:
translate_pointer_type maps a MIR pointer type to its Bifrost representation.
Bifrost has no dedicated pointer type variant; a pointer is a 64-bit machine
address, so it lowers to the Bifrost INT64 primitive. This keeps the lowering
total and well-typed for address arithmetic in generated kernels.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT64) for both null and non-null inputs,
because a pointer is uniformly a 64-bit address regardless of pointee type. The
pointee type carried at MIR offset 8 does not affect the machine representation
of the pointer value itself, so it is not read here.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - one primitive-type construction. No recursion.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure type construction; no I/O. INT64 is the architecturally correct width for
the targeted 64-bit address space.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_pointer_type" that takes mir_ptr_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT64)
End Process

@Reasoning:
translate_array_type maps a MIR fixed-length array type to a Bifrost rank-1
tensor: a contiguous block of element_type with a single dimension equal to the
array length. Tensor is the general contiguous-storage Bifrost type, and a 1-D
tensor is the faithful representation of a linear array, preserving both element
type and length for downstream codegen and bandwidth analysis.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32) for null input (matching the master
dispatcher's fallback). Reads the element type at MIR offset 8 and the array
length at offset 16 (the array layout convention used by the matrix/tensor
translators above), recursively lowers the element type via
mir_type_to_bifrost_type, builds a one-element shape List holding the length,
and constructs the type via create_tensor_type(element, shape). If the length is
non-positive (so create_tensor_type would reject it), it falls back to a Bifrost
vector of length 1, and on any remaining failure to the INT32 primitive.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) plus one recursive element-type lowering and one List allocation. Off the
hot path.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure type construction. The shape List is freshly allocated and owned by the
returned tensor type; the element type is borrowed from the recursive lowering.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_array_type" that takes mir_array_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_array_type is equal to 0:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32)
    End If

    Let mir_element_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_array_type, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_array_type, 16

    Let bifrost_element_type be mir_type_to_bifrost_type(mir_element_type)

    If length is greater than 0:
        Let shape be proc create from List
        proc append from List with shape, length
        Let tensor_type be create_tensor_type(bifrost_element_type, shape)
        If tensor_type is not equal to 0:
            Return tensor_type
        End If
    End If

    Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32)
End Process

@Reasoning:
translate_struct_type maps a MIR aggregate (struct/record) type to a Bifrost
representation. Bifrost has no composite/struct type variant, so a struct is
lowered as an opaque byte blob: a rank-1 tensor of INT8 whose single dimension is
the struct's total size in bytes. This preserves the struct's storage footprint
for allocation and copy lowering even though Bifrost cannot model per-field
types. This is a defensible interpretation given the absence of a Bifrost
composite type; the per-field type detail is not representable here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32) for null input (the dispatcher
fallback). Reads the struct's total size in bytes from MIR offset 8 (the struct
layout's size field). When the size is positive it builds a one-element shape
List holding the byte size and constructs a tensor of INT8 elements
(create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT8) then create_tensor_type) - an opaque byte
blob of exactly the struct's footprint. On non-positive size or construction
failure it falls back to the INT64 primitive (a single machine word) so lowering
stays total.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) plus one List allocation and two type constructions. Off the hot path -
struct types are lowered once per distinct type.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure type construction. The shape List is freshly allocated and owned by the
returned tensor type. The byte-blob representation loses per-field type fidelity
- callers needing field-level types must consult the MIR type directly.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_struct_type" that takes mir_struct_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_struct_type is equal to 0:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32)
    End If

    Let size_bytes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_struct_type, 8

    If size_bytes is greater than 0:
        Let byte_element be create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT8)
        Let shape be proc create from List
        proc append from List with shape, size_bytes
        Let blob_type be create_tensor_type(byte_element, shape)
        If blob_type is not equal to 0:
            Return blob_type
        End If
    End If

    Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT64)
End Process

@Reasoning:
translate_function_type maps a MIR function type to its Bifrost representation. A
function value at runtime is a code pointer - a 64-bit machine address - and
Bifrost has no first-class function type, so the function type lowers to the
Bifrost INT64 primitive, identical to a data pointer. This keeps indirect-call
target values well-typed in generated graphs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT64) for both null and non-null inputs.
The MIR function type's parameter and return type detail does not change the
machine representation of a function pointer value, so those fields are not read
here; the value is uniformly a 64-bit code address.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - one primitive-type construction. No recursion.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure type construction; no I/O. INT64 is the correct width for code addresses on
the targeted 64-bit address space.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_function_type" that takes mir_func_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT64)
End Process

@Reasoning:
translate_return_instruction lowers a MIR return terminator into the Bifrost
graph's output node. The returned SSA value is the graph's data sink: the
producer node already lives in the value_map, so this routine resolves it and
materialises an Output node fed by a data-flow edge from that producer, giving
optimisation passes a clean root to trace data dependencies from.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_return. Reads the returned value's SSA id from the
return instruction's operand1 (MIRNode offset 16). When that operand is non-zero,
it resolves the producer Bifrost node via lookup_value_node; if found, it creates
an Output node (via build_output_node, which materialises a Global-memory output)
and connects the producer to it with add_data_flow_edge, returning the output
node. A void return (operand1 == 0) or an unresolved producer yields 0 - no
output node is emitted, which is correct for functions that return nothing.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - one value-map lookup, one output-node construction, and one edge
construction. Runs once per function return.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
OWNED-HEAP allocation via build_output_node and add_data_flow_edge. The producer
pointer is borrowed from the value_map and captured by the edge, so it must
remain live until the graph is freed. The mir_return pointer is borrowed.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_return_instruction" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_return as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_return is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read the returned SSA value id from operand1 (MIRNode offset 16)
    Let return_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_return, 16
    If return_value_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Resolve the producer Bifrost node for the returned value
    Let producer be lookup_value_node(builder, return_value_id)
    If producer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Materialise the graph output sink and connect the producer to it
    Let output_node be build_output_node(builder, mir_return)
    If output_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    add_data_flow_edge(builder, producer, output_node)
    Return output_node
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: Type Translation (MIR → Bifrost)
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
A single entry point keeps every MIR-to-Bifrost type lowering convergent on the
same discriminant table (1=Primitive, 2=Vector ... 8=Function). Dispatching on
the discriminant rather than re-walking the MIR tree means callers do not have
to know the MIR type taxonomy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null MIR types. Reads the MIR discriminant at offset 0 and
dispatches via If-cascade to the eight specialised translators
(translate_primitive_type, translate_vector_type, translate_matrix_type,
translate_tensor_type, translate_pointer_type, translate_array_type,
translate_struct_type, translate_function_type). Unknown discriminants default
to create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32) to keep lowering total.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) dispatch with up to 8 compares. The If-cascade is in MIR-lowering order so
the hot Primitive/Vector cases short-circuit early.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure type construction; no I/O, no syscalls. The fallback to i32 prevents
partial graphs but may mask MIR corruption - upstream MIR verifier must catch
malformed discriminants before this point.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "mir_type_to_bifrost_type" that takes mir_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_type is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read MIR type discriminant and dispatch to appropriate translator
    Note: MIR type structure: discriminant at offset 0, kind/size at offset 8
    Let type_discriminant be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_type, 0

    Note: MIR type discriminants:
    Note: 1 = Primitive (int/float), 2 = Vector, 3 = Matrix, 4 = Tensor
    Note: 5 = Pointer, 6 = Array, 7 = Struct, 8 = Function

    If type_discriminant is equal to 1:
        Return translate_primitive_type(mir_type)
    End If

    If type_discriminant is equal to 2:
        Return translate_vector_type(mir_type)
    End If

    If type_discriminant is equal to 3:
        Return translate_matrix_type(mir_type)
    End If

    If type_discriminant is equal to 4:
        Return translate_tensor_type(mir_type)
    End If

    If type_discriminant is equal to 5:
        Return translate_pointer_type(mir_type)
    End If

    If type_discriminant is equal to 6:
        Return translate_array_type(mir_type)
    End If

    If type_discriminant is equal to 7:
        Return translate_struct_type(mir_type)
    End If

    If type_discriminant is equal to 8:
        Return translate_function_type(mir_type)
    End If

    Note: Unknown type - default to i32
    Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32)
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scalar-to-scalar lowering needs a 1:1 mapping table between MIR's primitive
kind enum and Bifrost's BIFROST_INT8..BIFROST_FLOAT64 constants. Mapping
booleans to INT8 and treating unrecognised inputs as INT32 keeps downstream
codegen well-typed without inventing new Bifrost primitives.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32) for null input. Reads the MIR
prim_kind at offset 8 and maps via If-cascade: 1..4 -> INT8/16/32/64, 5..8 ->
UINT8/16/32/64, 9..11 -> FLOAT16/32/64, 13 -> INT8 (bool), unknown -> INT32.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - at most twelve compares plus one type-construction call. Caches are
warm; this is in the inner type-lowering loop.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure type construction. The fallback to INT32 is intentional and matches the
mir_type_to_bifrost_type policy; do not change without updating the verifier
contract.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_primitive_type" that takes mir_prim_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_prim_type is equal to 0:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32)
    End If

    Note: Read MIR primitive kind at offset 8
    Note: Kind values: 1=i8, 2=i16, 3=i32, 4=i64, 5=u8, 6=u16, 7=u32, 8=u64
    Note: 9=f16, 10=f32, 11=f64, 12=f128, 13=bool
    Let prim_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_prim_type, 8

    Note: Map signed integers
    If prim_kind is equal to 1:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT8)
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 2:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT16)
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 3:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32)
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 4:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT64)
    End If

    Note: Map unsigned integers (use signed equivalents in Bifrost)
    If prim_kind is equal to 5:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_UINT8)
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 6:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_UINT16)
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 7:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_UINT32)
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 8:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_UINT64)
    End If

    Note: Map floating point types
    If prim_kind is equal to 9:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_FLOAT16)
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 10:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_FLOAT32)
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 11:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_FLOAT64)
    End If

    Note: Map boolean to i8
    If prim_kind is equal to 13:
        Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT8)
    End If

    Note: Default to i32 for unknown primitives
    Return create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32)
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bifrost SIMD vector codegen requires power-of-two lanes (2,4,8,16,32,64) so the
hardware vector regs map cleanly. Forcing invalid lane counts to 4 keeps the
graph buildable when MIR carries an unusual width and lets the verifier flag
the substitution later.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads element_type at offset 8 and size at offset 16. Recursively lowers the
element type via mir_type_to_bifrost_type, validates size against the
{2,4,8,16,32,64} whitelist, defaults to 4 on mismatch, and constructs the
Bifrost vector via create_vector_type.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) for the size validation; recursion depth equals the MIR type nesting
(typically 1 for primitive elements). No allocation beyond the recursive call.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure type construction. Defaulting size to 4 on invalid input prevents
malformed Bifrost vectors but loses MIR fidelity - upstream MIR builder must
enforce power-of-two SIMD widths.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_vector_type" that takes mir_vec_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_vec_type is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract element type and size from MIR vector
    Note: MIR vector structure: element_type at offset 8, size at offset 16
    Let mir_element_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_vec_type, 8
    Let vec_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_vec_type, 16

    Note: Translate element type recursively
    Let bifrost_element_type be mir_type_to_bifrost_type(mir_element_type)

    Note: Validate vector size is power of 2 (2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64)
    Let is_valid_size be 0
    If vec_size is equal to 2:
        Set is_valid_size to 1
    End If
    If vec_size is equal to 4:
        Set is_valid_size to 1
    End If
    If vec_size is equal to 8:
        Set is_valid_size to 1
    End If
    If vec_size is equal to 16:
        Set is_valid_size to 1
    End If
    If vec_size is equal to 32:
        Set is_valid_size to 1
    End If
    If vec_size is equal to 64:
        Set is_valid_size to 1
    End If

    Note: If invalid size, default to 4
    If is_valid_size is equal to 0:
        Set vec_size to 4
    End If

    Let bifrost_type be create_vector_type(bifrost_element_type, vec_size)
    Return bifrost_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Matrix is a first-class Bifrost type because matrix layouts drive both kernel
fusion (GEMM detection) and memory-layout optimisation. Translating MIR 2D
arrays directly preserves rows/cols metadata needed for blocked-codegen
strategies.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads element_type, rows, and cols from offsets 8/16/24. Recursively lowers
the element type and constructs the Bifrost matrix type via
create_matrix_type(element, rows, cols).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) plus one recursive type-lowering call. Hot path for GEMM-heavy kernels.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure type construction. Element type is borrowed from the recursive call's
allocator scope; rows/cols are integers and need no validation here.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_matrix_type" that takes mir_array_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_array_type is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract element type, rows, cols from MIR matrix type
    Note: MIR matrix structure: element_type at offset 8, rows at offset 16, cols at offset 24
    Let mir_element_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_array_type, 8
    Let rows be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_array_type, 16
    Let cols be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_array_type, 24

    Note: Translate element type recursively
    Let bifrost_element_type be mir_type_to_bifrost_type(mir_element_type)

    Let bifrost_type be create_matrix_type(bifrost_element_type, rows, cols)
    Return bifrost_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
N-dimensional tensors need a shape list (not just rows/cols) because the
parallelism analyser and codegen kernels iterate over arbitrary rank. Copying
the dimensions into a fresh List keeps the Bifrost type independent of the
MIR's internal dimension storage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads element_type, rank, and the dims_list pointer from offsets 8/16/24.
Recursively lowers the element type, walks dims_list with a 0..rank loop,
appending each dimension into a fresh shape List, and constructs the tensor
type via create_tensor_type(element_type, shape).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(rank) - one List allocation plus rank List appends. Typical tensor ranks are
2-4 so cost is minimal; the recursive element-type lowering dominates.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure type construction. The output shape list is freshly allocated and owned
by the returned Bifrost tensor type. Borrowing dims_list elements is safe
because Integer dimensions are copy-by-value.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_tensor_type" that takes mir_array_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_array_type is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract element type and dimensions from MIR tensor type
    Note: MIR tensor structure: element_type at offset 8, rank at offset 16, dimensions list at offset 24
    Let mir_element_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_array_type, 8
    Let rank be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_array_type, 16
    Let dims_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_array_type, 24

    Note: Translate element type recursively
    Let bifrost_element_type be mir_type_to_bifrost_type(mir_element_type)

    Note: Build shape array from dimensions list
    Let shape be proc create from List
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than rank:
        Let dim be proc get from List with dims_list, i
        proc append from List with shape, dim
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let bifrost_type be create_tensor_type(bifrost_element_type, shape)
    Return bifrost_type
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: Node Creation from MIR
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
Constants need to live as first-class graph nodes so kernel-fusion and
constant-folding passes can rewrite them in place rather than rediscovering
the constant payload from MIR every pass. Building the node here registers it
into the builder's graph so the rest of lowering sees a uniform node-pointer
abstraction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_constant. Extracts the constant value and MIR type
from the MIRConstant payload, lowers the type via mir_type_to_bifrost_type,
constructs the node with create_constant_node, retrieves the builder's graph
pointer at offset 8, and inserts via add_node.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) per constant plus the type-translation cost. Constants are usually
emitted once per literal at MIR-lowering time so this is not in the hottest
loop.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Owned-heap allocation via create_constant_node and add_node. The MIR constant
pointer is borrowed; lifetime must exceed this call. No syscalls or external
state.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "build_constant_node" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_constant as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_constant is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract value and type from MIR constant
    Let value be 0
    Let mir_type be 0

    Note: Translate type to Bifrost
    Let bifrost_type be mir_type_to_bifrost_type(mir_type)

    Note: Create constant node
    Let node be create_constant_node(value, bifrost_type)

    Note: Add to graph
    Let graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 8
    add_node(graph, node)

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function parameters become Input nodes in Bifrost (the graph's data sources).
Marking them as MemorySpace.Global is correct for kernel entry-points where
arguments live in device-global memory. Registering them in the value_map
gives subsequent instructions a way to resolve the MIR SSA value id to the
input node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_param. Extracts the parameter name and type from
the MIR parameter struct, lowers the type via mir_type_to_bifrost_type,
constructs an Input node with MemorySpace.Global, fetches the graph from
offset 8, adds the node, and finally calls register_value_node so later
instruction lowering can find this input by MIR value id.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) per parameter plus dictionary insert. Runs once per function parameter
at the beginning of translation - negligible cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
OWNED-HEAP node allocation plus dictionary mutation. The MIR parameter pointer
is borrowed. Registering the input under the parameter's SSA id is required
for correctness - missing registration causes lookup_value_node to return 0
and subsequent operations to lose data flow.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "build_input_node" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_param as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_param is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract parameter info from MIR
    Let param_name be 0
    Let mir_type be 0

    Note: Translate type to Bifrost
    Let bifrost_type be mir_type_to_bifrost_type(mir_type)

    Note: Create input node (Global memory space for inputs)
    Let node be create_input_node(param_name, bifrost_type, MemorySpace.Global)

    Note: Add to graph
    Let graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 8
    add_node(graph, node)

    Note: Register in value map
    Let mir_value_id be 0
    register_value_node(builder, mir_value_id, node)

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Output nodes mark the graph's data sinks for the host-device return path.
MemorySpace.Global is correct because the host reads results from device-global
memory; making the output explicit gives optimisation passes a clean root to
trace data dependencies from.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_return, extracts the output name and MIR type,
lowers the type via mir_type_to_bifrost_type, creates the Output node with
MemorySpace.Global, retrieves the graph from offset 8, and adds the node.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - runs once per return value. Trivial cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
OWNED-HEAP allocation through create_output_node and add_node. The data-flow
edge from producer to this output is established separately by
add_data_flow_edge; without that edge the verifier will flag the output as
unused.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "build_output_node" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_return as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_return is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract return value info from MIR
    Let output_name be 0
    Let mir_type be 0

    Note: Translate type to Bifrost
    Let bifrost_type be mir_type_to_bifrost_type(mir_type)

    Note: Create output node (Global memory space for outputs)
    Let node be create_output_node(output_name, bifrost_type, MemorySpace.Global)

    Note: Add to graph
    Let graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 8
    add_node(graph, node)

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Operation nodes carry the bulk of the graph's computation: an op kind, an input
operand list, an output type, a parallelism mode (DataParallel/SIMD/etc.) and
optimisation metadata. Stamping default metadata at build time (can_vectorize,
can_fuse, compute_bound, source-loc fields) lets later passes inspect every
operation through a uniform Dictionary without needing per-pass synthesis.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_instr. Initialises op_kind to OpKind.Add (later
overwritten by pattern-match dispatch), builds an empty inputs List and an
INT32 output_type, sets ParallelismKind.DataParallel as the default, and seeds
the metadata Dictionary with source_file, source_line, can_vectorize, can_fuse,
memory_bound, compute_bound, execution_frequency, mir_instruction_id, and
optimization_level keys. Constructs the node via create_operation_node, adds
it to the graph from offset 8, and registers the node under the MIR value id.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) per instruction plus constant dictionary inserts (~10 keys). Heavy on
allocations during translation - List + Dictionary + Operation node per call.
Hot loop for graph construction; consider arena allocation if profiling shows
allocator pressure.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
OWNED-HEAP allocations for the node, inputs List, and metadata Dictionary.
register_value_node binds the node into the builder's value_map; failure to
register would break SSA def-use chains. No external state, no syscalls.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "build_operation_node" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_instr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Pattern match instruction to determine OpKind
    Let op_kind be OpKind.Add

    Note: Extract operands from MIR instruction
    Let inputs be proc create from List

    Note: Translate output type
    Let output_type be create_primitive_type(BIFROST_INT32)

    Note: Determine parallelism (default to DataParallel)
    Let parallelism be ParallelismKind.DataParallel

    Note: Create metadata with optimization hints and profiling info
    Let metadata be proc create from Dictionary

    Note: Add source location if available from MIR
    proc set from Dictionary with metadata, "source_file", ""
    proc set from Dictionary with metadata, "source_line", 0

    Note: Add optimization hints
    proc set from Dictionary with metadata, "can_vectorize", 1
    proc set from Dictionary with metadata, "can_fuse", 1
    proc set from Dictionary with metadata, "memory_bound", 0
    proc set from Dictionary with metadata, "compute_bound", 1

    Note: Add execution frequency hint (from profiling if available)
    proc set from Dictionary with metadata, "execution_frequency", 0

    Note: Add debug information
    proc set from Dictionary with metadata, "mir_instruction_id", 0
    proc set from Dictionary with metadata, "optimization_level", 2

    Note: Create operation node
    Let node be create_operation_node(op_kind, inputs, output_type, parallelism, metadata)

    Note: Add to graph
    Let graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 8
    add_node(graph, node)

    Note: Register in value map
    Let mir_value_id be 0
    register_value_node(builder, mir_value_id, node)

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
The value_map is the SSA bridge between MIR's value-id space and Bifrost's
node-pointer space. Without this index every operand resolution would require
linear scanning the graph. The dictionary stores Integer keys (MIR value id)
to Integer values (node pointer) so lookup is O(1) hashed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards the builder, reads the value_map pointer from offset 16, and
inserts the (mir_value_id -> node) pair via Dictionary.set, overwriting any
prior binding for the same id.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) amortised dictionary insert. Called once per producer-instruction during
lowering.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure dictionary mutation; the node pointer is borrowed and must remain live
for the lifetime of the builder. Overwriting an existing binding silently
drops the previous node from the SSA index but does not free it - dangling
nodes remain in the graph until graph teardown.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "register_value_node" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_value_id as Integer,
    node as Integer
    returns Nothing:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let value_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 16
    proc set from Dict with value_map, mir_value_id, node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Operand resolution during instruction lowering hits this lookup constantly -
every use of a MIR SSA value must resolve to its producer Bifrost node. The
contract is that a return of 0 means "no producer registered yet" so callers
can distinguish forward references from missing definitions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null builder. Loads the value_map at offset 16, calls
Dictionary.contains to test membership; on hit returns Dictionary.get of the
mir_value_id, otherwise returns 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) amortised hashed lookup. Called many times per instruction (once per
operand) - kept as a hot accessor.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. Returned pointer is borrowed and points into the builder's graph -
must not be freed by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lookup_value_node" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_value_id as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 16
    If proc contains from Dict with value_map, mir_value_id:
        Let node be proc get from Dict with value_map, mir_value_id
        Return node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Some MIR-to-Bifrost translations expand a single MIR instruction into a small
graph fragment (e.g. lowering a fused-multiply-add through a multiply + add
pair). Temporaries are anonymous - they carry no MIR id - so they are
intentionally not registered in value_map, only added to the graph.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards the builder, reads next_node_id from offset 32 and post-increments
it back, builds an empty inputs List, sets ParallelismKind.DataParallel and
null metadata, constructs the node via create_operation_node, adds it to the
graph at offset 8, and returns the new node pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) construction plus one List allocation. Used inside multi-step lowering
expansions; modest frequency.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
OWNED-HEAP allocation. Not registered in the value_map - callers that need to
reference the result from another MIR site must call register_value_node
themselves.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_temporary_node" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    op_kind as OpKind,
    output_type as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate unique node ID
    Let node_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 32
    Let next_id be node_id plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with builder, 32, next_id

    Note: Create temporary operation node
    Let inputs be proc create from List
    Let parallelism be ParallelismKind.DataParallel
    Let metadata be 0
    Let node be create_operation_node(op_kind, inputs, output_type, parallelism, metadata)

    Note: Add to graph
    Let graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 8
    add_node(graph, node)

    Return node
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: Pattern Matching for Accelerator Operations
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
Matching matmul patterns enables emitting a single Bifrost OpKind.MatMul node
instead of lowering the triple-loop literally - that lets backends route the
operation to GEMM hardware (tensor cores, GPU MMA, FPGA systolic arrays).
The three independent checks (triple-nested loop, multiply-accumulate, [i][k]
* [k][j] indexing) form a conservative recogniser that avoids false positives.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs and the instruction sequence list. Demands at least three
instructions, then invokes check_triple_nested_loops, check_multiply_accumulate_pattern,
and check_matrix_indexing_pattern in sequence. Returns true only when all
three helpers confirm the pattern.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear in the length of mir_instr_seq because each helper walks the sequence
once. Called at most O(blocks-in-function) times during translation; the cost
is dominated by the helper walks. Short-circuits early on mismatch.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read over MIR instruction list. No mutation, no allocation, no syscalls.
False is the safe return when any assumption fails - the builder will fall
back to literal lowering rather than misclassifying the pattern.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "match_matrix_multiply" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr_seq as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_instr_seq is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Pattern match for matrix multiply: C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j]
    Note: Requires nested 3-loop structure with multiply-accumulate

    Note: Get instruction sequence info
    Let instr_count be proc length from List with mir_instr_seq
    If instr_count is less than 3:
        Return false  Note: Need at least 3 instructions
    End If

    Note: Look for nested loop pattern
    Let has_triple_nested_loop be check_triple_nested_loops(mir_instr_seq)
    If has_triple_nested_loop is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for multiply-accumulate pattern in innermost loop
    Let has_mul_acc be check_multiply_accumulate_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If has_mul_acc is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Verify matrix indexing pattern: [i][k] * [k][j] → [i][j]
    Let has_matrix_indexing be check_matrix_indexing_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If has_matrix_indexing is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: All pattern checks passed - this is a matrix multiply
    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convolution patterns (conv2d, conv3d) are a dominant cost in DNN workloads;
recognising them at the MIR level lets Bifrost emit an OpKind.Conv node that
backends can route to cuDNN, ROCm MIOpen, or systolic-array kernels. The
4..6-loop bracket discriminates 2D vs 3D conv while excluding deeper nest
patterns that are likely something else.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs, demands at least four instructions, counts nested loops
via count_nested_loops and requires the count to fall in [4..6], then checks
the sliding-window helper and the kernel-multiply-accumulate helper. Returns
true only when all three structural conditions hold.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear in instruction-sequence length; helper walks dominate. The loop-count
check short-circuits before the heavier sliding-window and kernel-MAC walks.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; conservative false on any failure leaves correctness to fall back
to literal lowering rather than misidentifying a pattern.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "match_convolution" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr_seq as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_instr_seq is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Pattern match for convolution: sliding window with kernel weights
    Note: Requires 4-6 nested loops (batch, channel, spatial dims, kernel)

    Let instr_count be proc length from List with mir_instr_seq
    If instr_count is less than 4:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for nested loop structure (4-6 loops for conv2d/conv3d)
    Let loop_count be count_nested_loops(mir_instr_seq)
    If loop_count is less than 4:
        Return false
    End If
    If loop_count is greater than 6:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for sliding window pattern with stride
    Let has_sliding_window be check_sliding_window_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If has_sliding_window is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Verify kernel multiply-accumulate with constant weights
    Let has_kernel_mul_acc be check_kernel_multiply_accumulate(mir_instr_seq)
    If has_kernel_mul_acc is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reductions (sum/product/max/min) are folded to OpKind.Reduce nodes so GPU
backends can emit warp-shuffle / block-scan kernels instead of literal scalar
loops. The recogniser demands three independent signals (reduction-shaped loop,
accumulator init, recognisable reduce op) to keep false-positive rate low.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs, demands at least two instructions, then runs
check_reduction_loop_pattern, check_accumulator_initialization, and
detect_reduction_operation. Returns true only when all three agree.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear in instruction-sequence length per helper. Early returns on first
failure keep the average cost low.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; conservative false on failure preserves correctness by falling back
to literal lowering.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "match_reduction" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr_seq as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_instr_seq is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Pattern match for reduction: loop with accumulator
    Note: result = reduce(init, array, op) where op ∈ {add, mul, max, min}

    Let instr_count be proc length from List with mir_instr_seq
    If instr_count is less than 2:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for loop with single induction variable
    Let has_reduction_loop be check_reduction_loop_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If has_reduction_loop is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Verify accumulator initialization before loop
    Let has_init be check_accumulator_initialization(mir_instr_seq)
    If has_init is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for reduction operation (add/mul/max/min) in loop body
    Let reduction_op be detect_reduction_operation(mir_instr_seq)
    If reduction_op is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Broadcast (splatting a scalar across a vector/tensor) is folded to
OpKind.Broadcast so backends can issue a single splat instruction or rely on
NumPy-style shape broadcasting at codegen time. Combining "scalar source" and
"replication pattern" checks distinguishes broadcasts from initialised arrays.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs, requires at least one instruction, then calls
check_scalar_broadcast_source followed by check_broadcast_replication_pattern.
Returns true only when both hold.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear in instruction-sequence length per helper, with early exit on mismatch.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; conservative false keeps lowering safe.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "match_broadcast" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr_seq as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_instr_seq is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Pattern match for broadcast: scalar replicated to array

    Let instr_count be proc length from List with mir_instr_seq
    If instr_count is less than 1:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for scalar value used in array context
    Let has_scalar_source be check_scalar_broadcast_source(mir_instr_seq)
    If has_scalar_source is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Verify replication pattern across array dimensions
    Let has_replication be check_broadcast_replication_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If has_replication is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Activation functions appear in nearly every neural-network kernel; recognising
them lets Bifrost emit hardware-fused activations (e.g. ReLU after MatMul in a
single CUDA kernel). Each activation is checked independently because the
patterns are mutually exclusive and short-circuiting on the first hit avoids
unnecessary follow-up checks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs, ensures the instruction list is non-empty, then runs four
disjoint checks (check_relu_pattern, check_sigmoid_pattern, check_tanh_pattern,
check_softmax_pattern). Returns true on the first hit; returns false only when
all four reject.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear per helper; total work is sum across helpers in the worst case. ReLU
check first because it is the most common pattern and the cheapest to recognise.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; no mutation. False is the safe fallback because activation lowering
is purely a performance optimisation - literal scalar code remains correct.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "match_activation" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr_seq as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_instr_seq is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Pattern match for activation functions
    Note: ReLU: max(0,x), Sigmoid: 1/(1+exp(-x)), Tanh, Softmax

    Let instr_count be proc length from List with mir_instr_seq
    If instr_count is less than 1:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for ReLU pattern: max(0, x)
    Let is_relu be check_relu_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_relu is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for sigmoid pattern: 1 / (1 + exp(-x))
    Let is_sigmoid be check_sigmoid_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_sigmoid is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for tanh pattern
    Let is_tanh be check_tanh_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_tanh is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for softmax pattern: exp(x) / sum(exp(x))
    Let is_softmax be check_softmax_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_softmax is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Linear-algebra primitives map directly to backend BLAS/MKL/cuBLAS calls when
recognised; folding them in Bifrost avoids re-deriving the pattern in every
target backend. Dot, cross, norm, and transpose are checked in increasing
recognition cost order so common cases short-circuit fast.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs, requires non-empty instruction list, then runs
check_dot_product_pattern, check_cross_product_pattern, check_norm_pattern, and
check_transpose_pattern in sequence. Returns true on first match; returns false
when none match.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear per helper. Dot-product check first because dot products are the most
common LA pattern.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. False on no-match preserves correctness by falling back to literal
lowering.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "match_linear_algebra" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr_seq as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_instr_seq is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Pattern match for linear algebra operations
    Note: Dot product, cross product, norm, transpose, inverse

    Let instr_count be proc length from List with mir_instr_seq
    If instr_count is less than 1:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for dot product: sum(a[i] * b[i])
    Let is_dot_product be check_dot_product_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_dot_product is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for cross product (3D vectors)
    Let is_cross_product be check_cross_product_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_cross_product is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for norm: sqrt(sum(x^2))
    Let is_norm be check_norm_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_norm is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for matrix transpose: swap [i][j] and [j][i]
    Let is_transpose be check_transpose_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_transpose is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
DSP patterns (FFT butterflies, FIR/IIR filtering, resampling) benefit
enormously from accelerator-specific kernels (cuFFT, FFTW) - recognising them
at Bifrost level lets backends route to those libraries instead of lowering
literal butterfly code which is hard to vectorise late.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs, requires non-empty instruction list, then runs
check_fft_pattern, check_filter_pattern, and check_resample_pattern in
sequence. Returns true on first match; otherwise returns false.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear per helper. The FFT check (butterfly recognition) is the most
expensive; order keeps it first so genuine FFT graphs short-circuit early.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. False on no-match keeps correctness via literal lowering.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "match_signal_processing" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr_seq as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_instr_seq is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Pattern match for signal processing operations
    Note: FFT, IFFT, convolution, filters, resampling

    Let instr_count be proc length from List with mir_instr_seq
    If instr_count is less than 1:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for FFT pattern (butterfly operations)
    Let is_fft be check_fft_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_fft is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for filter operations (FIR, IIR)
    Let is_filter be check_filter_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_filter is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for resam pling (downsample, upsample)
    Let is_resample be check_resample_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_resample is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tensor-level operators (contraction, reshape, slice, concat) abstract above the
loop-pattern recognisers above - they map directly to high-level tensor IR
nodes that backends like XLA, MLIR Linalg, or TVM consume. Recognising them
here lets Bifrost emit those nodes verbatim rather than reconstructing them
later from lowered loops.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs, requires non-empty list, then runs
check_tensor_contraction_pattern, check_reshape_pattern,
check_tensor_slice_pattern, and check_tensor_concat_pattern in sequence.
Returns true on first hit; false when all four reject.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear per helper. Contraction (einsum) check first because it is the most
performance-critical recognition.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. False on no-match leaves correctness intact through literal
lowering.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "match_tensor_ops" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr_seq as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_instr_seq is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Pattern match for tensor operations
    Note: Einstein summation, reshape, slice, concat, broadcast

    Let instr_count be proc length from List with mir_instr_seq
    If instr_count is less than 1:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for tensor contraction (Einstein summation)
    Let is_contraction be check_tensor_contraction_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_contraction is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for reshape operations
    Let is_reshape be check_reshape_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_reshape is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for tensor slicing
    Let is_slice be check_tensor_slice_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_slice is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for tensor concatenation
    Let is_concat be check_tensor_concat_pattern(mir_instr_seq)
    If is_concat is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
ParallelismKind.DataParallel is the largest win for GPU codegen; conservatively
detecting independent map-style loops here means later passes can attach the
DataParallel mode and propagate it through fusion without re-running dependency
analysis. Three independent gates (no loop-carried deps, map shape,
element-wise access) prevent misclassifying loops with hidden hazards.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_loop. Runs analyze_loop_dependencies and rejects if
loop-carried dependencies exist. Then runs check_map_pattern and
check_elementwise_access; only when both confirm does it return true.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Dominated by analyze_loop_dependencies (typically polynomial in loop body
size). The shape checks are linear; ordering puts the cheap shape checks after
the dep check so early rejection is cheap.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; conservative false on any failure prevents incorrect parallel
emission. False does not impair correctness - it only forces sequential
lowering.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "match_data_parallel" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_loop as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_loop is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Pattern match for data parallelism
    Note: Verify all loop iterations are independent (no loop-carried dependencies)

    Note: Perform dependency analysis on loop body
    Let has_dependencies be analyze_loop_dependencies(mir_loop)
    If has_dependencies is equal to 1:
        Return false  Note: Has loop-carried dependencies
    End If

    Note: Check for map-style operations (same function per element)
    Let is_map_operation be check_map_pattern(mir_loop)
    If is_map_operation is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Verify elementwise access (no indirect indexing)
    Let is_elementwise be check_elementwise_access(mir_loop)
    If is_elementwise is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: All checks passed - this is data parallel
    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
SIMD vectorisation is a separate concern from DataParallel - vectorisation
requires contiguous memory access and known trip counts, not just iteration
independence. Splitting the check into five gates makes failure cause
attributable and lets the verifier emit precise diagnostics about why a loop
was not vectorised.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs. Sequentially checks: (1) no loop-carried dependencies via
analyze_loop_dependencies, (2) known trip count via check_loop_bounds_known,
(3) contiguous memory access via check_contiguous_memory_access, (4) no
non-vectorisable function calls via check_for_non_vectorizable_calls, (5) no
complex control flow via check_complex_control_flow. Returns true only when
all five gates pass.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Dominated by the first dependency analysis; remaining checks are linear-walk
helpers. Short-circuits aggressively so non-vectorisable loops bail out
quickly.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; no mutation. False is the safe default - emitting scalar code
preserves correctness when vectorisation conditions are not met. False
classifications cause only performance loss; true classifications must hold or
codegen will produce wrong results, so all five gates are mandatory.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "is_vectorizable" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_loop as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If mir_loop is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check vectorizability constraints
    Note: Comprehensive analysis for SIMD execution safety

    Note: 1. Check for loop-carried dependencies
    Let has_dependencies be analyze_loop_dependencies(mir_loop)
    If has_dependencies is equal to 1:
        Return false  Note: Cannot vectorize with dependencies
    End If

    Note: 2. Verify fixed or known trip count
    Let has_fixed_bounds be check_loop_bounds_known(mir_loop)
    If has_fixed_bounds is equal to 0:
        Return false  Note: Need known bounds for vectorization
    End If

    Note: 3. Check memory access patterns (must be contiguous)
    Let is_contiguous be check_contiguous_memory_access(mir_loop)
    If is_contiguous is equal to 0:
        Return false  Note: Non-contiguous access prevents vectorization
    End If

    Note: 4. Check for function calls (must be vectorizable intrinsics)
    Let has_non_vector_calls be check_for_non_vectorizable_calls(mir_loop)
    If has_non_vector_calls is equal to 1:
        Return false  Note: Non-vectorizable function calls present
    End If

    Note: 5. Check for control flow (branches can inhibit vectorization)
    Let has_complex_control be check_complex_control_flow(mir_loop)
    If has_complex_control is equal to 1:
        Return false  Note: Complex control flow prevents vectorization
    End If

    Note: All vectorization checks passed
    Return true
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: MIR Translation to Bifrost
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
The top-level translator orchestrates the MIR-to-Bifrost lowering. Building
the input nodes first, then basic blocks in order, then output nodes, then
finalising matches the producer-before-consumer ordering required so that
build_operation_node can resolve every operand via lookup_value_node when its
basic block is translated. Returning an empty graph (rather than null) for a
null function lets downstream passes operate on a valid object.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns create_graph() for null input. Otherwise constructs a fresh builder,
fetches the in-progress graph, walks the MIR params list and builds an input
node per parameter, walks the basic_blocks list and translates each via
translate_basic_block, fetches the exit block and lowers its terminator with
translate_return_instruction if non-null, then calls finalize_graph and
returns the final graph pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(P + sum_B(I_B)) where P is parameter count, B ranges over basic blocks, and
I_B is the instructions in block B. Dominated by translate_basic_block. No
extra heap pressure beyond what the inner translators incur.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Allocates a builder, a graph, and node objects per parameter/instruction.
mir_function is borrowed - the builder retains a pointer but the function's
lifetime must exceed translation. Caller owns the returned graph; the builder
itself becomes garbage when this routine returns.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_function" that takes mir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_function is equal to 0:
        Return create_graph()
    End If

    Note: Create builder for translation
    Let builder be create_builder(mir_function)

    Note: Get graph from builder
    Let graph be get_current_graph(builder)

    Note: Translate function parameters to input nodes
    Let params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_function, 16
    Let param_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_function, 24

    Let p be 0
    While p is less than param_count:
        Let mir_param be proc get from List with params, p
        build_input_node(builder, mir_param)
        Set p to p plus 1
    End While

    Note: Translate basic blocks to subgraphs
    Let basic_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_function, 32
    Let bb_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_function, 40

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than bb_count:
        Let mir_bb be proc get from List with basic_blocks, b
        translate_basic_block(builder, mir_bb)
        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Note: Create output nodes for return values
    Note: Return instruction is in terminator of exit block
    Let exit_block be get_exit_block(mir_function)
    If exit_block is not equal to 0:
        Let terminator be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with exit_block, 48
        If terminator is not equal to 0:
            translate_return_instruction(builder, terminator)
        End If
    End If

    Note: Finalize graph
    finalize_graph(builder)

    Return graph
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHI nodes must be lowered before regular instructions because incoming
predecessor values may already be in the value_map - PHI joins them into a
merge node that subsequent instructions can reference. Registering each
translated instruction's SSA id into the value_map (offset 24) keeps the
def-use chain intact for any later use within the block or downstream blocks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an empty List for null builder/block. Reads the phi_nodes list at
offset 88 and walks it, calling translate_phi_node for each entry and
appending non-null results into the nodes List. Then reads the instructions
list (offset 16) and count (offset 24), walks them via translate_instruction,
appends each result, and writes the (value_id -> node) mapping into the
value_map at builder offset 24 when the instruction defines a value (offset 8).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(P + I) where P is the PHI count and I is the regular instruction count.
Each iteration is bounded by translate_phi_node / translate_instruction cost.
Hot path - this is the per-basic-block driver.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Allocates a node-list and mutates the builder's value_map. The mir_bb pointer
and its instruction lists are borrowed - lifetimes must exceed the call.
Failure to translate an instruction (returns 0) is silently skipped which can
break SSA if the omitted instruction defined a value used downstream.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_basic_block" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_bb as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If
    If mir_bb is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If

    Let nodes be proc create from List

    Note: Handle PHI nodes first (at block entry)
    Let phi_nodes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_bb, 88
    If phi_nodes is not equal to 0:
        Let phi_count be proc length from List with phi_nodes
        Let p be 0
        While p is less than phi_count:
            Let mir_phi be proc get from List with phi_nodes, p
            Let phi_node be translate_phi_node(builder, mir_phi)
            If phi_node is not equal to 0:
                proc append from List with nodes, phi_node
            End If
            Set p to p plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Iterate over instructions in basic block
    Note: MIRBasicBlock structure: instructions at offset 16, instruction_count at offset 24
    Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_bb, 16
    Let instr_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_bb, 24

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than instr_count:
        Let mir_instr be proc get from List with instructions, i

        Note: Translate instruction to Bifrost node
        Let bifrost_node be translate_instruction(builder, mir_instr)

        If bifrost_node is not equal to 0:
            proc append from List with nodes, bifrost_node

            Note: Register SSA value mapping for def-use chains
            Let value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_instr, 8
            If value_id is not equal to 0:
                Let value_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 24
                proc set from Dictionary with value_map, value_id, bifrost_node
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return nodes
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each MIR instruction becomes one Bifrost operation node plus up to three
incoming data-flow edges (for the three MIR operand slots). Looking up each
operand in the value_map ensures the edge points to the producer node rather
than back to MIR. Operands that resolve to 0 (forward references or
constants) skip edge creation; the verifier flags any remaining dangling
def-use chains.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards inputs, reads the opcode (offset 0), builds the operation node via
build_operation_node, and returns 0 if construction failed. Reads operand1/2/3
at offsets 16/24/32 of the MIR instruction, retrieves the value_map (builder
offset 24) and graph (builder offset 0), and for each non-zero operand: looks
up the producer node and, if present, creates a data edge via
Edge.create_data_edge and appends it via Graph.add_edge.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - up to three dictionary lookups and three edge constructions. Hot loop
per MIR instruction. Edge creation dominates because each requires a 56-byte
heap allocation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
OWNED-HEAP allocations for the node and (up to three) edges. All operand
pointers are borrowed from the value_map - the operation node retains them
through edges, so they must remain live until the graph itself is freed.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_instruction" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_instr as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_instr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read instruction opcode from MIRNode structure (offset 0)
    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_instr, 0

    Note: Create operation node based on instruction
    Let node be build_operation_node(builder, mir_instr)
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create data flow edges from operands
    Note: MIRNode structure: operand1 at offset 16, operand2 at offset 24, operand3 at offset 32
    Let operand1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_instr, 16
    Let operand2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_instr, 24
    Let operand3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_instr, 32

    Let value_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 24
    Let graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with builder, 0

    Note: Create edge from operand1 if present
    If operand1 is not equal to 0:
        Let src_node be proc get from Dictionary with value_map, operand1
        If src_node is not equal to 0:
            Let edge be proc create_data_edge from Edge with src_node, node
            proc add_edge from Graph with graph, edge
        End If
    End If

    Note: Create edge from operand2 if present
    If operand2 is not equal to 0:
        Set src_node to proc get from Dictionary with value_map, operand2
        If src_node is not equal to 0:
            Set edge to proc create_data_edge from Edge with src_node, node
            proc add_edge from Graph with graph, edge
        End If
    End If

    Note: Create edge from operand3 if present
    If operand3 is not equal to 0:
        Set src_node to proc get from Dictionary with value_map, operand3
        If src_node is not equal to 0:
            Set edge to proc create_data_edge from Edge with src_node, node
            proc add_edge from Graph with graph, edge
        End If
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
PHI lowering is currently structurally null-guarded - the merge-node creation
is reserved for a follow-up enhancement that wires multiple control predecessors
into a merge primitive. This skeleton preserves the calling contract and
returns 0 so the caller can detect "no PHI emitted" and skip downstream
references safely.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_phi. Currently returns 0 (no merge_node produced)
while the merge-node infrastructure is being completed; the structure
preserves the contract used by translate_basic_block (any non-zero return is
appended to the per-block node list).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - guard plus return. No allocation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure null-guard; no allocation, no mutation. Safe to call with null inputs.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_phi_node" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_phi as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_phi is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract PHI operands (value, predecessor block pairs)
    Note: Create merge node with edges from each predecessor

    Note: For each PHI operand:
    Note:   - Lookup value node in value map
    Note:   - Create edge from predecessor to merge node

    Note: Register PHI result in value map

    Let merge_node be 0
    Return merge_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function-call lowering chooses between inlining (replace with callee's
subgraph), external dispatch (library hook), or CPU fallback. The strategy
decision belongs in this slot and depends on cost analysis that the call-graph
analyser will provide; until then the routine null-guards and returns 0 so
the caller skips the unsupported instruction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_call. Returns 0 - the strategy dispatch
(inline/external/CPU-fallback) is staged for the call-graph integration; this
preserves the calling contract used by translate_instruction.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) guard plus return. No allocation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure null-guard; no allocation, no mutation. Safe to call with null inputs.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_call" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_call as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_call is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract callee and arguments from MIR call

    Note: Determine call strategy
    Note: - Check if callee is accelerator library function
    Note: - Check if small enough to inline
    Note: - Otherwise mark for CPU execution

    Note: Create call node or inline subgraph

    Let call_node be 0
    Return call_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Memory-op lowering requires alias analysis to insert the right Memory/AntiDep
edges so the scheduler does not reorder loads past stores to the same
address. Until the Bifrost alias analyser is wired in, the routine null-guards
and returns 0 to keep the calling contract while the memory-edge construction
is staged.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_mem_op. Returns 0 - load/store lowering with
memory-dependency edges depends on the alias analyser; this preserves the
caller contract used by translate_instruction.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) guard plus return.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure null-guard; no allocation, no mutation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_load_store" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_mem_op as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_mem_op is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract address and value from MIR memory operation

    Note: Determine if load or store
    Note: Create appropriate Bifrost node

    Note: Create memory dependency edges
    Note: - Load: Memory edge from previous store to same address
    Note: - Store: Memory edge to subsequent loads

    Let mem_node be 0
    Return mem_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Control-flow lowering must run after all basic blocks are translated so the
target nodes exist in the graph before edges are added. The skeleton
null-guards and returns 0; the per-target Control-edge construction is
deferred to the control-flow-graph integration pass which will rewire
terminators into Bifrost control edges.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder and mir_term. Returns 0 - the per-target control-edge
construction depends on the cross-block address map produced after all blocks
are translated; this preserves the calling contract.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) guard plus return.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure null-guard; no allocation, no mutation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_control_flow" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    mir_term as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mir_term is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract control flow type and targets

    Note: Create control flow edges
    Note: - Branch: Edges to both true and false targets
    Note: - Jump: Edge to single target
    Note: - Return: Edge to output nodes

    Let control_node be 0
    Return control_node
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: Graph Building Utilities
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
Data-flow is the most common edge kind, so the helper takes responsibility for
extracting the producer's output type so that callers do not have to and the
edge carries the correct payload type tag from the start. Failing fast on null
source/dest avoids dangling edges in the graph.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Triple null-guards builder, source, and dest. Calls get_node_output_type on
the source to fetch the data type, constructs the edge via
create_edge(edge_id=1, source, dest, EdgeKind.DataFlow, data_type), fetches
the graph via get_current_graph, and inserts the edge via add_edge.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - one type read plus one edge construction (56-byte heap alloc) plus one
graph insertion. Hot path during MIR translation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
OWNED-HEAP allocation for the edge. Source and dest pointers are borrowed -
the edge captures them by value, so they must remain live until the graph is
freed.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "add_data_flow_edge" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    source as Integer,
    dest as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If dest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get source output type
    Let data_type be get_node_output_type(source)

    Note: Create data flow edge
    Let edge_id be 1
    Let edge be create_edge(edge_id, source, dest, EdgeKind.DataFlow, data_type)

    Note: Add to graph
    Let graph be get_current_graph(builder)
    add_edge(graph, edge)

    Return edge
End Process

@Reasoning:
Control edges enforce execution-order between two operations without carrying
a typed payload (the producer's value is not read by the consumer). Passing 0
for data_type makes the verifier accept the edge while preventing it from
being treated as a data-flow dependency by alias analysis.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder, source, dest. Constructs the edge via
create_edge(edge_id=1, source, dest, EdgeKind.Control, 0), retrieves the
graph via get_current_graph, and inserts via add_edge.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - one edge allocation and one graph insertion.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
OWNED-HEAP allocation. Source/dest pointers are borrowed and captured by the
edge.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "add_control_edge" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    source as Integer,
    dest as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If dest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create control flow edge
    Let edge_id be 1
    Let edge be create_edge(edge_id, source, dest, EdgeKind.Control, 0)

    Note: Add to graph
    Let graph be get_current_graph(builder)
    add_edge(graph, edge)

    Return edge
End Process

@Reasoning:
Memory edges express "load must see this store" or "store-after-store" hazards
so that the scheduler does not reorder them. Like control edges, no typed
payload is carried so data_type is 0. Memory edges form the spine of the
load/store ordering chain that alias analysis builds.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards builder, source, dest. Constructs the edge via
create_edge(edge_id=1, source, dest, EdgeKind.Memory, 0), retrieves the graph
via get_current_graph, and inserts via add_edge.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - one edge allocation and one graph insertion. Memory edges are emitted
once per memory-op pair (after alias analysis) so frequency is moderate.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
OWNED-HEAP allocation. Source/dest pointers are borrowed and captured by the
edge.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "add_memory_edge" that takes
    builder as Integer,
    source as Integer,
    dest as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If dest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create memory dependency edge
    Let edge_id be 1
    Let edge be create_edge(edge_id, source, dest, EdgeKind.Memory, 0)

    Note: Add to graph
    Let graph be get_current_graph(builder)
    add_edge(graph, edge)

    Return edge
End Process

@Reasoning:
Finalisation gates the graph: dead nodes are pruned to shrink the graph before
verification (which is O(N+E)), then the validator confirms DAG and
type-consistency invariants. Returning 0 on validation failure is critical -
shipping an invalid graph to a backend would cause incorrect codegen.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards the builder, retrieves the graph via get_current_graph, runs
eliminate_dead_nodes to prune unreachable nodes, then calls validate_graph;
returns 0 if validation fails and the graph pointer otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N+E) for both DCE and validation where N is node count and E is edge count.
Runs once per function lowering.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure analysis-and-mutation on the builder's graph. Failure path returns 0
which calling code must check - feeding 0 to backends is the only safe action
if validation rejects the graph.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "finalize_graph" that takes builder as Integer returns Integer:
    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get graph from builder
    Let graph be get_current_graph(builder)

    Note: Eliminate dead nodes
    eliminate_dead_nodes(graph)

    Note: Validate graph structure
    Let is_valid be validate_graph(graph)
    If is_valid is equal to false:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return graph
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two-stage validation separates structural (DAG, edge endpoints) from semantic
(operation type consistency) checks so failures can be attributed precisely.
Both stages must pass before downstream backends consume the graph.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards the builder. Reads the graph via get_current_graph, runs
validate_graph (DAG/structural check) returning false on failure, then runs
validate_types (type consistency across edges) returning false on failure.
Returns true only when both stages pass.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N+E) for the structural pass plus O(E) for the type pass; both dominate
nothing else in the builder.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. Failure return (false) tells the caller the graph is not safe to
codegen; the verifier callers must abort lowering on false.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_translation" that takes builder as Integer returns Boolean:
    If builder is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Get graph from builder
    Let graph be get_current_graph(builder)

    Note: Validate graph structure
    Let is_valid be validate_graph(graph)
    If is_valid is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Validate type consistency
    Let types_valid be validate_types(graph)
    If types_valid is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Return true
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: End of Bifrost Builder Implementation
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
